The Humanity Score Protocol v2.1: A Geometrically and Probabilistically Unified Framework for Authenticity Quantification

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Status: Pure mathematical specification – no empirical claims

---

Abstract

We present a fully deterministic, mathematically closed protocol for computing a continuous authenticity score H(a) \in [0,1] for any digital account a, based solely on observable behavior: temporal action patterns, linguistic content, network interactions, and collective synchrony. The protocol fuses four orthogonal signals – Hawkes branching ratio (temporal self‑excitation), manifold geometry of text embeddings (local intrinsic dimensionality and Hessian curvature), spectral graph invariants (normalized Fiedler value, triadic closure exponent, conductance p‑values), and a time‑decaying synchronicity tensor – into a logistic score with geometric (product + quadratic) fusion. All hyperparameters are derived analytically from assumed Beta, Gamma, and Normal prior families for human vs. non‑human distributions, eliminating any empirical calibration. A Bayesian immune system maintains weight distributions via clipped, surprisal‑throttled variational updates, anchored by cryptographically verified human accounts and protected by a (2,3)‑threshold consensus rule. We prove bounded parameter drift under adversarial poisoning (Theorem 1), provide PAC‑Bayesian generalization bounds, establish convergence to an oracle score under ergodic streams (Theorem 2), and quantify sensitivity to streaming approximations. The protocol is modular, interpretable, and fully verifiable. No empirical benchmarks are reported; all claims are theoretical.

---

1. Introduction

The proliferation of non‑human accounts – from simple scripted bots to advanced large language models (LLMs) and coordinated disinformation networks – poses a fundamental challenge to online platforms, governance systems, and digital trust. Distinguishing human from synthetic behavior is not merely a classification problem; it requires a continuous, interpretable, and adversarially robust measure of authenticity that can operate in real time without retraining on large datasets.

Existing approaches fall into three categories, each with limitations:

1. Heuristic rule‑based systems (e.g., CAPTCHAs, rate limits) are easily bypassed by sophisticated adversaries and offer no fine‑grained score.
2. Black‑box deep learning classifiers achieve high empirical accuracy but lack transparency, are vulnerable to adversarial examples, and require periodic retraining on labeled datasets that quickly become outdated.
3. Single‑signal statistical methods (e.g., only temporal point processes or only network motifs) are insufficient because modern bots can mimic one signal while failing on others.

The Humanity Score Protocol (HSP) addresses these gaps by combining four mathematically orthogonal signals – temporal, linguistic, network, and collective – into a single score H(a). Each signal is chosen for its theoretical separation between human and non‑human behavior under well‑studied generative models. The protocol is:

· Interpretable: Each component corresponds to a clear behavioral hypothesis (e.g., humans exhibit self‑exciting action patterns with circadian rhythms; synthetic text lies on lower‑dimensional, negatively curved manifolds).
· Modular: Layers are independent and can be refined or replaced without retraining the whole system.
· Adversarially robust: A Bayesian immune system with gradient clipping, surprisal‑throttled learning, and anchor‑based consensus provably limits parameter drift under poisoning attacks.
· Purely mathematical: All constants are derived from prior distributions, not from empirical fitting. No datasets, benchmarks, or physical implementations are used.

This document presents HSP v2.1, the culmination of iterative theoretical hardening. Section 2 defines the axiomatic priors and adversarial model. Section 3 details the four layers with closed‑form loss functions and bounded approximations. Section 4 describes the geometric fusion and calibration. Section 5 presents the Bayesian immune system with proven robustness guarantees. Section 6 outlines the modular architecture and streaming approximations. Section 7 states the theoretical guarantees and limitations. Section 8 concludes.

The intended audience is mathematicians, cryptographers, and system architects interested in provably verifiable authenticity scoring without reliance on empirical black boxes. No empirical validation is provided or claimed; the value of HSP lies in its internal consistency, transparency, and mathematical rigor.

