2.1 Axiomatic Priors for Human vs. Non‑Human Behavior

Let \mathcal{A} be the set of all accounts. For each account a \in \mathcal{A}, we observe:

· Temporal sequence T_a = \{t_1, t_2, \dots\} of action times (posts, replies, etc.).
· Linguistic sequence X_a = \{x_1, x_2, \dots\} of text content.
· Interaction graph G = (V,E) undirected, derived from replies, retweets, mentions, follows.

We assume that there exists an underlying latent type Y_a \in \{\text{Human}, \text{Non-Human}\} with prior probabilities \pi_H = \pi_N = 0.5 (uninformative). The behavior of an account is governed by a set of parameters \Theta_a = (\theta_B, \theta_L, \theta_N, \theta_C) where each component follows a known prior distribution conditional on Y_a.

2.1.1 Temporal Prior (Hawkes Branching Ratio)

For a human account, the branching ratio n = \int_0^\infty \phi(\tau)d\tau follows a Beta distribution:

n \sim \text{Beta}(\alpha_B^H = 5,\; \beta_B^H = 3)

Mean \mathbb{E}[n] = 5/8 = 0.625, variance \text{Var}(n) = 5\cdot3/(8^2\cdot9) \approx 0.026. For a non‑human (e.g., Poisson process or scripted bot), the branching ratio is concentrated near zero:

n \sim \text{Beta}(\alpha_B^N = 1,\; \beta_B^N = 10)

Mean \mathbb{E}[n] = 1/11 \approx 0.09. These choices are theoretically motivated: human social activity exhibits self‑excitation (branching ratio > 0.5), while non‑human activity is either memoryless (Poisson, n=0) or weakly excited (n<0.2).

2.1.2 Linguistic Prior (Local Intrinsic Dimensionality)

Let \text{LID}(a) be the median local intrinsic dimensionality of the embeddings of a's posts (see §2.3). For a human:

\text{LID} \sim \text{Gamma}(k_L^H = 20,\; \theta_L^H = 0.6)

Mean 12, variance 7.2. For synthetic text (LLM‑generated):

\text{LID} \sim \text{Gamma}(k_L^N = 10,\; \theta_L^N = 0.5)

Mean 5, variance 2.5. These values reflect the hypothesis that human language occupies a higher‑dimensional semantic manifold due to idiosyncratic topic shifts and creative leaps.

2.1.3 Network Prior (Triadic Closure Exponent)

For a human, the triadic closure exponent \alpha in t_i \propto k_i^\alpha follows a truncated normal:

\alpha \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_N^H = 2.0,\; \sigma_N^H = 0.2),\quad \alpha \in [1,3]

For a botnet (coordinated synthetic accounts):

\alpha \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_N^N = 1.2,\; \sigma_N^N = 0.3),\quad \alpha \in [0.5,2.5]

The human value \alpha \approx 2 is derived from the theory of weak ties and triadic closure in social networks.

2.1.4 Collective Prior (Synchronicity)

For a set A of unrelated human accounts, the synchronicity metric \Psi(A) (defined in §2.4) decays as O(1/\sqrt{T}) with observation time T. Formally, under an inhomogeneous Poisson null model with circadian rate, the distribution of \Psi is approximated by an exponential distribution with rate \lambda_C = 10 (mean 0.1):

\Psi \sim \text{Exp}(\lambda_C = 10)

For a synchronized botnet, \Psi is high and follows a Beta distribution:

\Psi \sim \text{Beta}(\alpha_C^N = 4,\; \beta_C^N = 2)

Mean 2/3 \approx 0.667.

