2.2 Adversarial Model

Let an adversary \mathcal{A} control a set \mathcal{B} \subset \mathcal{A} of bot accounts. The adversary aims to maximize the fraction of \mathcal{B} with H(a) > 0.5.

Capabilities:

· Generate arbitrary text, timing, and interaction patterns.
· Observe the protocol’s output H(a) (white‑box).
· Computational resources bounded by polynomial time in |\mathcal{A}|.
· Cannot break cryptographic primitives (e.g., hash functions, proof‑of‑human‑work puzzles).

Objective: Minimize \mathbb{E}_{a \in \mathcal{B}}[1 - H(a)] subject to a budget on total deviation from human priors measured by Kullback‑Leibler (KL) divergence per account \text{KL}(a \parallel \mathcal{P}_{\text{human}}) \le D_{\max}.

Definition 1 (Adversarial Budget). For a given adversary, the total divergence budget is B = \sum_{a \in \mathcal{B}} \text{KL}(a \parallel \mathcal{P}_{\text{human}}). The adversary is D_{\max}‑bounded if \max_{a \in \mathcal{B}} \text{KL}(a \parallel \mathcal{P}_{\text{human}}) \le D_{\max}.

