2.4 Layer L: Linguistic Manifold Geometry

2.4.1 Embeddings and LID

Let \mathcal{T}: \text{text} \to \mathbb{R}^d be a fixed transformer embedding (e.g., d = 1536). For a post x, let \mathbf{v} = \mathcal{T}(x). The Local Intrinsic Dimensionality (LID) at a point \mathbf{v} is defined via the nearest neighbor distances:

\text{LID}(\mathbf{v}) = \left( \frac{1}{|N(\mathbf{v}, r)|} \sum_{\mathbf{u} \in N(\mathbf{v}, r)} \log \frac{\|\mathbf{u} - \mathbf{v}\|}{r} \right)^{-1}

where N(\mathbf{v}, r) is the set of neighbors within radius r in the global embedding space of all posts. For each account a, we take the median LID over its posts: \text{LID}_a = \text{median}_{x \in X_a} \text{LID}(\mathcal{T}(x)).

Relative LID: To achieve invariance to the embedding model, we normalize by the theoretical prior predictive median for humans:

\text{LID}_{\text{rel}}(a) = \frac{\text{LID}_a}{\text{LID}_0}

where \text{LID}_0 is the median of the Gamma prior \text{Gamma}(20,0.6), i.e., \text{LID}_0 \approx 11.9. This is a fixed constant.

2.4.2 Semantic Curvature via Hessian Trace

Let p_{\text{LLM}}(x) be the probability assigned to text x by a fixed reference LLM (e.g., a pre‑trained autoregressive model). Define the curvature proxy:

\kappa_{\text{prob}}(x) = \operatorname{tr}\left( \nabla^2 \log p_{\text{LLM}}(x) \right)

where the gradient is taken with respect to the embedding vector of x (or with respect to the logits). For synthetic text, \kappa_{\text{prob}}(x) is systematically negative (local maxima of the LLM’s likelihood). For human text, it fluctuates around zero.

Define the variance of \kappa_{\text{prob}} across all posts of account a:

\mathcal{V}_a = \frac{1}{|X_a|-1} \sum_{x \in X_a} \left( \kappa_{\text{prob}}(x) - \bar{\kappa}_a \right)^2

2.4.3 Linguistic Loss

\mathcal{L}_L(a) = 1 - \exp\left( -\frac{\text{LID}_{\text{rel}}(a) \cdot \mathcal{V}_a}{\tau} \right)

where \tau = \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{P}_{\text{human}}}[\text{LID} \cdot \mathcal{V}] is computed analytically assuming independence and the prior moments:

\tau = \mathbb{E}[\text{LID}] \cdot \mathbb{E}[\mathcal{V}]

