2.5 Layer N: Network Spectral and Triadic Invariants

2.5.1 Graph Construction

From the interaction graph G = (V,E) (undirected), we compute:

· Degree k_i for each node.
· Triangle count t_i for each node (number of triangles containing i).

2.5.2 Triadic Closure Exponent

Assume t_i = c k_i^{\alpha} for large k_i. We estimate \alpha by method of moments:

\hat{\alpha} = \frac{\log\left( \frac{\sum_i t_i k_i}{\sum_i t_i} \right) - \log\left( \frac{\sum_i k_i^2}{\sum_i k_i} \right)}{\log\left( \frac{\sum_i k_i^2}{\sum_i k_i} \right) - \log\left( \frac{\sum_i k_i}{\sum_i 1} \right)}

This closed‑form estimate avoids iterative fitting. Then the triadic loss component is:

\mathcal{L}_{N,\text{triad}}(a) = \frac{|\hat{\alpha} - 2|}{2 + |\hat{\alpha} - 2|}

which saturates at 1 for large deviations.

2.5.3 Spectral Gap Ratio

Let L = D - A be the graph Laplacian, with eigenvalues 0 = \lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \dots \le \lambda_n. The normalized Fiedler value is:

\lambda_2^{\text{norm}} = \frac{\lambda_2}{\lambda_{\max}}

We compare to a degree‑corrected stochastic block model (DCSBM) null. Under the DCSBM with the same degree sequence and community assignment (obtained via Louvain), the expected second eigenvalue \lambda_2^{\text{null}} can be approximated by the spectral radius of a certain matrix. Define:

\Delta_{\lambda} = \frac{\lambda_2^{\text{norm}}}{\lambda_2^{\text{null}}} - 1

If \Delta_{\lambda} < 0 (graph is less connected than null), it may indicate a bot cluster. We set:

\mathcal{L}_{N,\text{spectral}} = \max(0, -\Delta_{\lambda})

2.5.4 Conductance and Collusive Cells

For a cluster S (from Louvain), the conductance is:

\Phi(S) = \frac{|\partial S|}{\min(\text{vol}(S), \text{vol}(V\setminus S))}

where \partial S is the edge boundary and \text{vol}(S) = \sum_{i\in S} k_i. Under the DCSBM null, the distribution of \Phi(S) for a given cluster size is approximately Beta. We compute the p‑value:

p_{\text{cond}}(S) = P_{\text{DCSBM}}(\Phi(S) \le \Phi_{\text{obs}})

Then the conductance loss for an account a in cluster S is:

\mathcal{L}_{N,\text{cond}}(a) = 1 - p_{\text{cond}}(S)

If p_{\text{cond}} < 0.05, the cluster is considered a collusive cell and \mathcal{L}_{N,\text{cond}} = 1.

2.5.5 Combined Network Loss

\mathcal{L}_N(a) = \frac{1}{3}\left( \mathcal{L}_{N,\text{triad}}(a) + \mathcal{L}_{N,\text{spectral}}(a) + \mathcal{L}_{N,\text{cond}}(a) \right)

