2.6 Layer C: Collective Synchronicity

2.6.1 Time‑Decaying Cross‑Correlation

For each account a, define binary activity X_a(t) with bin width \Delta = 10 seconds. For a set of accounts A (typically a cluster from the network layer), define the time‑decaying cross‑correlation:

\mathcal{X}_{ij}(t) = \frac{\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-|u|/\tau_c} X_i(t-u) X_j(t) du}{\sqrt{\int X_i^2 \int X_j^2}}

where \tau_c = 24\ \text{hours} / (2\pi) \approx 3.82\ \text{hours} (derived from the circadian period). The synchronicity metric for set A is:

\Psi(A) = \frac{1}{|A|(|A|-1)} \sum_{i\neq j} \max_{t} \mathcal{X}_{ij}(t)

2.6.2 Baseline and Excess

Under an inhomogeneous Poisson null with circadian rate \lambda(t) (the same periodic spline as in Layer B), the expected value of \Psi(A) for unrelated humans is:

\Psi_{\text{base}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{T}} + c_{\text{circ}}

where c_{\text{circ}} is a small constant derived from the Fourier transform of \lambda(t). The excess synchronicity is:

\Psi_{\text{excess}} = \max(0, \Psi(A) - \Psi_{\text{base}})

2.6.3 Size Normalization

Normalize by the expected maximum cross‑correlation under the null for a set of size m = |A|:

\Psi_{\text{norm}} = \frac{\Psi_{\text{excess}}}{\mathbb{E}[\max_{i\neq j} \mathcal{X}_{ij}]_{\text{null}}}

Using extreme value theory for Gaussian processes:

\mathbb{E}[\max] \approx \sqrt{2\log(m)} + \frac{\gamma}{\sqrt{2\log(m)}}

where \gamma \approx 0.5772 is Euler’s constant.

2.6.4 Collective Loss

\mathcal{L}_C(A) = \min\left(1, \frac{\Psi_{\text{norm}}}{c_0}\right)

with c_0 = 2 (theoretical threshold from Gumbel distribution). For each account a \in A, we set \mathcal{L}_C(a) = \mathcal{L}_C(A).

Additional Fourier test: Compute the periodogram of the aggregated activity \sum_{a\in A} X_a(t). If the power at any non‑circadian frequency exceeds the 99^{\text{th}} percentile of the theoretical null distribution (chi‑squared with 2 degrees of freedom), set \mathcal{L}_C(A) = 1 directly.

