7.2 Distributed and Parallel Architecture

For large‑scale deployment, the protocol must be distributed across multiple nodes. We propose a shared‑nothing architecture with the following components:

7.2.1 Sharding by Account ID

Accounts are assigned to shards using a consistent hash function. Each shard maintains:

· Local copy of the global embedding index (for LID) – updated asynchronously.
· Local subgraph of interactions (only edges where both endpoints are in the same shard; cross‑shard edges are stored in a separate edge exchange).
· Local anchor subsets (each shard gets a disjoint set of anchors, but consensus requires cross‑shard communication).

7.2.2 Global Aggregators

Three global services run on dedicated nodes:

· Embedding aggregator: Maintains the reservoir sample of embeddings for LID computation. Receives embeddings from all shards, samples uniformly, and broadcasts the updated sample periodically.
· Graph spectral aggregator: Collects edge updates from all shards, runs incremental Lanczos on the full graph, and broadcasts \lambda_2^{\text{norm}} and cluster assignments (Louvain) every hour.
· Consensus coordinator: Collects anchor accuracy reports from shards, decides whether to accept or reject weight updates, and broadcasts the global \mu, \Sigma to all shards.

7.2.3 Communication Complexity

Let S be the number of shards, N total accounts. The per‑shard communication per hour is:

· Embedding updates: O(\text{sample size}) = O(10^5) embeddings, each of size d=1536 floats → ~600 MB.
· Graph updates: number of new edges per hour, typically O(N) but amortized.
· Consensus messages: O(S) per update cycle.

This is feasible with modern networking.

