7.4 Governance and Transparency

The protocol is designed to be transparent and auditable:

· All parameters are publicly documented (as above).
· The anchor set \mathcal{A}_0 is published as a list of account IDs (with hashed identifiers to preserve privacy).
· The weight vector \mu and covariance \Sigma are periodically published on a tamper‑proof ledger (e.g., blockchain).
· Anyone can independently compute H(a) for any account using the published parameters and the raw data (which is assumed to be publicly available or can be requested).

Governance adjustments: If the community detects a systematic bias (e.g., certain human groups consistently receive low scores), the prior distributions can be updated via a governance vote. The updated priors must be mathematically justified (e.g., using a larger Beta variance) and do not require empirical retraining. This maintains the protocol’s theoretical integrity.

