**Appendix B: Layer Loss Functions (Unified Likelihood-Ratio Form)**

For every layer \(i\), the sufficient statistic \(s_i(a)\) (e.g., \(\hat{n}_a\), \(\operatorname{LID}_{\text{rel}} \cdot \mathcal{V}_a\), \(\hat{\alpha}\), \(\Psi_{\text{norm}}\)) yields densities \(p_i^H\) and \(p_i^N\) under the human/non-human priors.  

The loss is  
\[
\mathcal{L}_i(a) = 1 - \frac{p_i^H(s_i(a))}{p_i^H(s_i(a)) + p_i^N(s_i(a))}.
\]  
This form is always in \([0,1]\), equals 0 when data strongly favors human, equals 1 when it favors non-human, and is monotone in KL divergence (Lemma 3, main text).

**B.1 Layer B (Temporal)**  
\(s_B = \hat{n}_a\), \(p^H = \operatorname{Beta}(5,3)\), \(p^N = \operatorname{Beta}(1,10)\).  
Variational posterior mean \(\hat{n}_a\) from Gamma-process ELBO (Lemma 1).

**B.2 Layer L (Linguistic)**  
\(s_L = \operatorname{LID}_{\text{rel}}(a) \cdot \mathcal{V}_a\), with \(\operatorname{LID}_{\text{rel}} = \operatorname{LID}_a / 11.9\) (median of human Gamma prior).  
\(\mathcal{V}_a\) is sample variance of \(\kappa_{\text{prob}}\). Joint density obtained by independence assumption on Gamma marginals.

**B.3 Layer N (Network)**  
\(s_N = (\hat{\alpha}, \Delta_\lambda, 1 - p_{\text{cond}})\). Triadic component uses method-of-moments \(\hat{\alpha}\); spectral and conductance use DCSBM null (Beta-approximated p-value).

**B.4 Layer C (Synchronicity)**  
\(s_C = \Psi_{\text{norm}}\). Excess over Poisson baseline normalized by extreme-value expectation \(\sqrt{2\log m} + \gamma / \sqrt{2\log m}\).

