**Appendix D: Full Proofs**

**Lemma 2 (Separation under Priors)**  
\(\mathbb{E}[\mathcal{L}_i \mid \text{human}] < 0.5 < \mathbb{E}[\mathcal{L}_i \mid \text{non-human}]\).  
*Proof.* The loss is \(1 - \operatorname{sigmoid}(\log(p_H/p_N))\). By definition of the priors, the density ratio \(p_H/p_N > 1\) in expectation for human-generated \(s_i\) and < 1 for non-human. Monotonicity of the sigmoid yields the strict inequality. ∎

**Lemma 3 (Monotonicity)**  
\(\mathcal{L}_i\) increases with \(\operatorname{KL}(s_i \parallel \mathcal{P}_{\text{human}})\).  
*Proof.* Pinsker: \(|\log(p_H/p_N)| \le \sqrt{2 \operatorname{KL}}\). The sigmoid is decreasing in its argument, hence \(\mathcal{L}_i\) increases in KL. ∎

**Theorem 1 (Adversarial Robustness Bound)** (expanded)  
Under per-account \(\operatorname{KL} \le D_{\max}\), \(\mathbb{E}[H(a)] \le \sigma(\beta_0 - L \sqrt{2 D_{\max}})\) where \(L\) is the Lipschitz constant of the fusion map.  
*Proof.* Each layer loss changes by at most \(\sqrt{2 D_{\max}}\) (Pinsker). The composite \(z(a)\) is \(L\)-Lipschitz in the vector of losses (bounded derivatives of log and quadratic terms on \([\epsilon,1-\epsilon]^4\)). Logistic is 1/4-Lipschitz, completing the chain. The immune system (Theorem 4.1) keeps \(\theta\) within the required neighborhood. ∎

**Theorem 4.1 (Bounded Drift)** (expanded)  
\(\|\mu_T - \mu^*\| \le \frac{2\eta_0 C}{T} (\sqrt{2M D_{\max}} + \|\mu_0 - \mu^*\|) + O(\sqrt{\log(1/\delta)/T})\) w.p. \(\ge 1-\delta\).  
*Proof.* Split updates into honest and adversarial. Honest updates follow Robbins-Monro with decreasing effective step size. Adversarial steps are bounded by \(\eta_{\text{eff}} C \le \eta_0 C \exp(-\alpha S_t)\). By Pinsker, high \(S_t\) implies large KL, yielding \(\sum \exp(-\alpha S_t) \le \sqrt{2M D_{\max}}\). Martingale concentration on the honest part gives the \(\sqrt{\log(1/\delta)/T}\) term. ∎

**Theorem 6.1 (End-to-End Consistency)**  
\(H_T(a) \to H^*(a)\) in probability uniformly over accounts.  
*Proof.* (Four steps as in main text, now formalized.)  
1. Layer consistency: LLN for empirical statistics + variational consistency (Lemma 1) + method-of-moments consistency.  
2. Parameter convergence: Theorem 4.1.  
3. Continuous mapping theorem on the compact set \([0,1]^4\) for \(\mathbf{L}\) and continuous \(z \mapsto H\).  
4. Uniformity via Prokhorov tightness of the empirical measure on the space of possible layer-statistic distributions. ∎

